            Polish government reshuffling
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong
              >Summary: Polish PM Donald Tusk restructured his government after
              an election loss to strengthen stability and ties with the
              US.</strong
            >
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Polish PM Donald Tusk has
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-analysis-h1-9-reshuffled-his-cabinet"
              target="_blank"
              >reshuffled his cabinet</a
            >
            following a presidential election defeat and growing tensions within
            his ruling coalition. He elevated the foreign minister to deputy
            prime minister to give Poland stronger leadership in international
            and EU affairs, created a “superministry” to control both fiscal and
            economic policy, and appointed incoming ministers for energy and
            justice.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The why:</strong> The shakeup comes after Tusk’s preferred
            presidential candidate, Rafał Trzaskowski (mayor of Warsaw),
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-analysis-h1-10-lost-in-june"
              target="_blank"
              >lost in June</a
            >
            to Karol Nawrocki (right-wing candidate), giving the presidency and
            its power to veto laws to the nationalist right. Meanwhile,
            far-right groups like Konfederacja are gaining followers with their
            nationalist and libertarian messages, pressuring Tusk to consolidate
            control.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The outlook:</strong> Despite political polarization at
            home, Poland’s mainstream parties (covering about 85-90% of the
            political spectrum) remain united on foreign policy: opposing
            Russia, backing Ukraine, and supporting NATO and US cooperation.
            With key figures from the reshuffle being experienced,
            English‑speaking, and well‑connected in Washington, Poland is
            expected to remain a dependable defense and security partner for the
            US.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
