        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              Nash equilibrium is a central idea in game theory, where no player
              can gain an advantage by changing their strategy unless the other
              players change theirs too. Source: The Peninsula Foundation
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Game theory analyzes strategic situations
            where the outcome of one player depends on the choices of others. It
            was formalized in the 1940s by mathematician John von Neumann and
            economist Oskar Morgenstern, and it became an important tool during
            the Cold War to model nuclear deterrence (convincing an enemy not to
            attack by threatening a strong response). Today, it is widely used
            in politics, economics, and military planning (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-foundations-h1-17-game-theory-101"
              target="_blank"
              >game theory 101</a
            >).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The example:</strong> In a potential Iran-Israel nuclear
            standoff, Iran must decide whether to continue its nuclear program,
            knowing Israel might attack. Similarly, Israel would need to
            consider whether to strike, aware that Iran could retaliate. This is
            called a “game” because it’s a situation of strategic independence:
            each side’s best choice depends on what it thinks the other side
            will do.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The application:</strong> In
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-foundations-h1-18-international-relations"
              target="_blank"
              >international relations</a
            >, game theory can show the sequence of moves and decisions
            (extensive model), compare all possible strategies and preferred
            results (strategic model), or measure the value each partner brings
            to an alliance (coalition model). It provides a clear framework
            through different scenarios and consequences. While it doesn’t
            provide a definitive answer, it helps decision makers understand how
            their choices and assumptions about others’ choices can shape the
            final outcome.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            See what game theory reveals about war
